 202 #  operations. (+, -).
 203 def _stata_elapsed_date_to_datetime_vec(dates, fmt) -> Series:
 204     """
 205     Convert from SIF to datetime. https://www.stata.com/help.cgi?datetime
 206 
 207     Parameters
 208     ----------
 209     dates : Series
 210         The Stata Internal Format date to convert to datetime according to fmt
 211     fmt : str
 212         The format to convert to. Can be, tc, td, tw, tm, tq, th, ty
 213         Returns
 214 
 215     Returns
 216     -------
 217     converted : Series
 218         The converted dates
 219 
 220     Examples
 221     --------
 222     >>> dates = pd.Series([52])
 223     >>> _stata_elapsed_date_to_datetime_vec(dates , "%tw")
 224     0   1961-01-01
 225     dtype: datetime64[ns]
 226 
 227     Notes
 228     -----
 229     datetime/c - tc
 230         milliseconds since 01jan1960 00:00:00.000, assuming 86,400 s/day
 231     datetime/C - tC - NOT IMPLEMENTED
 232         milliseconds since 01jan1960 00:00:00.000, adjusted for leap seconds
 233     date - td
 234         days since 01jan1960 (01jan1960 = 0)
 235     weekly date - tw
 236         weeks since 1960w1
 237         This assumes 52 weeks in a year, then adds 7 * remainder of the weeks.
 238         The datetime value is the start of the week in terms of days in the
 239         year, not ISO calendar weeks.
 240     monthly date - tm
 241         months since 1960m1
 242     quarterly date - tq
 243         quarters since 1960q1
 244     half-yearly date - th
 245         half-years since 1960h1 yearly
 246     date - ty
 247         years since 0000
 248     """
 249     MIN_YEAR, MAX_YEAR = Timestamp.min.year, Timestamp.max.year
 250     MAX_DAY_DELTA = (Timestamp.max - datetime.datetime(1960, 1, 1)).days
 251     MIN_DAY_DELTA = (Timestamp.min - datetime.datetime(1960, 1, 1)).days
 252     MIN_MS_DELTA = MIN_DAY_DELTA * 24 * 3600 * 1000
 253     MAX_MS_DELTA = MAX_DAY_DELTA * 24 * 3600 * 1000
 254 
 255     def convert_year_month_safe(year, month) -> Series:
 256         """
 257         Convert year and month to datetimes, using pandas vectorized versions
 258         when the date range falls within the range supported by pandas.
 259         Otherwise it falls back to a slower but more robust method
 260         using datetime.
 261         """
 262         if year.max() < MAX_YEAR and year.min() > MIN_YEAR:
 263             return to_datetime(100 * year + month, format="%Y%m")
 264         else:
 265             index = getattr(year, "index", None)
 266             return Series(
 267                 [datetime.datetime(y, m, 1) for y, m in zip(year, month)], index=index
 268             )
 269 
 270     def convert_year_days_safe(year, days) -> Series:
 271         """
 272         Converts year (e.g. 1999) and days since the start of the year to a
 273         datetime or datetime64 Series
 274         """
 275         if year.max() < (MAX_YEAR - 1) and year.min() > MIN_YEAR:
 276             return to_datetime(year, format="%Y") + to_timedelta(days, unit="d")
 277         else:
 278             index = getattr(year, "index", None)
 279             value = [
 280                 datetime.datetime(y, 1, 1) + relativedelta(days=int(d))
 281                 for y, d in zip(year, days)
 282             ]
 283             return Series(value, index=index)
 284 
 285     def convert_delta_safe(base, deltas, unit) -> Series:
 286         """
 287         Convert base dates and deltas to datetimes, using pandas vectorized
 288         versions if the deltas satisfy restrictions required to be expressed
 289         as dates in pandas.
 290         """
 291         index = getattr(deltas, "index", None)
 292         if unit == "d":
 293             if deltas.max() > MAX_DAY_DELTA or deltas.min() < MIN_DAY_DELTA:
 294                 values = [base + relativedelta(days=int(d)) for d in deltas]
 295                 return Series(values, index=index)
 296         elif unit == "ms":
 297             if deltas.max() > MAX_MS_DELTA or deltas.min() < MIN_MS_DELTA:
 298                 values = [
 299                     base + relativedelta(microseconds=(int(d) * 1000)) for d in deltas
 300                 ]
 301                 return Series(values, index=index)
 302         else:
 303             raise ValueError("format not understood")
 304         base = to_datetime(base)
 305         deltas = to_timedelta(deltas, unit=unit)
 306         return base + deltas
 307 
 308     # TODO: If/when pandas supports more than datetime64[ns], this should be
 309     # improved to use correct range, e.g. datetime[Y] for yearly
 310     bad_locs = np.isnan(dates)
 311     has_bad_values = False
 312     if bad_locs.any():
 313         has_bad_values = True
 314         data_col = Series(dates)
 315         data_col[bad_locs] = 1.0  # Replace with NaT
 316     dates = dates.astype(np.int64)
 317 
 318     if fmt.startswith(("%tc", "tc")):  # Delta ms relative to base
 319         base = stata_epoch
 320         ms = dates
 321         conv_dates = convert_delta_safe(base, ms, "ms")
 322     elif fmt.startswith(("%tC", "tC")):
 323 
 324         warnings.warn("Encountered %tC format. Leaving in Stata Internal Format.")
 325         conv_dates = Series(dates, dtype=np.object)
 326         if has_bad_values:
 327             conv_dates[bad_locs] = NaT
 328         return conv_dates
 329     # Delta days relative to base
 330     elif fmt.startswith(("%td", "td", "%d", "d")):
 331         base = stata_epoch
 332         days = dates
 333         conv_dates = convert_delta_safe(base, days, "d")
 334     # does not count leap days - 7 days is a week.
 335     # 52nd week may have more than 7 days
 336     elif fmt.startswith(("%tw", "tw")):
 337         year = stata_epoch.year + dates // 52
 338         days = (dates % 52) * 7
 339         conv_dates = convert_year_days_safe(year, days)
 340     elif fmt.startswith(("%tm", "tm")):  # Delta months relative to base
 341         year = stata_epoch.year + dates // 12
 342         month = (dates % 12) + 1
 343         conv_dates = convert_year_month_safe(year, month)
 344     elif fmt.startswith(("%tq", "tq")):  # Delta quarters relative to base
 345         year = stata_epoch.year + dates // 4
 346         quarter_month = (dates % 4) * 3 + 1
 347         conv_dates = convert_year_month_safe(year, quarter_month)
 348     elif fmt.startswith(("%th", "th")):  # Delta half-years relative to base
 349         year = stata_epoch.year + dates // 2
 350         month = (dates % 2) * 6 + 1
 351         conv_dates = convert_year_month_safe(year, month)
 352     elif fmt.startswith(("%ty", "ty")):  # Years -- not delta
 353         year = dates
 354         first_month = np.ones_like(dates)
 355         conv_dates = convert_year_month_safe(year, first_month)
 356     else:
 357         raise ValueError(f"Date fmt {fmt} not understood")
 358 
 359     if has_bad_values:  # Restore NaT for bad values
 360         conv_dates[bad_locs] = NaT
 361 
 362     return conv_dates
 363

 365 def _datetime_to_stata_elapsed_vec(dates: Series, fmt: str) -> Series:
 366     """
 367     Convert from datetime to SIF. https://www.stata.com/help.cgi?datetime
 368 
 369     Parameters
 370     ----------
 371     dates : Series
 372         Series or array containing datetime.datetime or datetime64[ns] to
 373         convert to the Stata Internal Format given by fmt
 374     fmt : str
 375         The format to convert to. Can be, tc, td, tw, tm, tq, th, ty
 376     """
 377     index = dates.index
 378     NS_PER_DAY = 24 * 3600 * 1000 * 1000 * 1000
 379     US_PER_DAY = NS_PER_DAY / 1000
 380 
 381     def parse_dates_safe(dates, delta=False, year=False, days=False):
 382         d = {}
 383         if is_datetime64_dtype(dates.dtype):
 384             if delta:
 385                 time_delta = dates - stata_epoch
 386                 d["delta"] = time_delta._values.astype(np.int64) // 1000  # microseconds
 387             if days or year:
 388                 date_index = DatetimeIndex(dates)
 389                 d["year"] = date_index.year
 390                 d["month"] = date_index.month
 391             if days:
 392                 days_in_ns = dates.astype(np.int64) - to_datetime(
 393                     d["year"], format="%Y"
 394                 ).astype(np.int64)
 395                 d["days"] = days_in_ns // NS_PER_DAY
 396 
 397         elif infer_dtype(dates, skipna=False) == "datetime":
 398             if delta:
 399                 delta = dates._values - stata_epoch
 400 
 401                 def f(x: datetime.timedelta) -> float:
 402                     return US_PER_DAY * x.days + 1000000 * x.seconds + x.microseconds
 403 
 404                 v = np.vectorize(f)
 405                 d["delta"] = v(delta)
 406             if year:
 407                 year_month = dates.apply(lambda x: 100 * x.year + x.month)
 408                 d["year"] = year_month._values // 100
 409                 d["month"] = year_month._values - d["year"] * 100
 410             if days:
 411 
 412                 def g(x: datetime.datetime) -> int:
 413                     return (x - datetime.datetime(x.year, 1, 1)).days
 414 
 415                 v = np.vectorize(g)
 416                 d["days"] = v(dates)
 417         else:
 418             raise ValueError(
 419                 "Columns containing dates must contain either "
 420                 "datetime64, datetime.datetime or null values."
 421             )
 422 
 423         return DataFrame(d, index=index)
 424 
 425     bad_loc = isna(dates)
 426     index = dates.index
 427     if bad_loc.any():
 428         dates = Series(dates)
 429         if is_datetime64_dtype(dates):
 430             dates[bad_loc] = to_datetime(stata_epoch)
 431         else:
 432             dates[bad_loc] = stata_epoch
 433 
 434     if fmt in ["%tc", "tc"]:
 435         d = parse_dates_safe(dates, delta=True)
 436         conv_dates = d.delta / 1000
 437     elif fmt in ["%tC", "tC"]:
 438         warnings.warn("Stata Internal Format tC not supported.")
 439         conv_dates = dates
 440     elif fmt in ["%td", "td"]:
 441         d = parse_dates_safe(dates, delta=True)
 442         conv_dates = d.delta // US_PER_DAY
 443     elif fmt in ["%tw", "tw"]:
 444         d = parse_dates_safe(dates, year=True, days=True)
 445         conv_dates = 52 * (d.year - stata_epoch.year) + d.days // 7
 446     elif fmt in ["%tm", "tm"]:
 447         d = parse_dates_safe(dates, year=True)
 448         conv_dates = 12 * (d.year - stata_epoch.year) + d.month - 1
 449     elif fmt in ["%tq", "tq"]:
 450         d = parse_dates_safe(dates, year=True)
 451         conv_dates = 4 * (d.year - stata_epoch.year) + (d.month - 1) // 3
 452     elif fmt in ["%th", "th"]:
 453         d = parse_dates_safe(dates, year=True)
 454         conv_dates = 2 * (d.year - stata_epoch.year) + (d.month > 6).astype(np.int)
 455     elif fmt in ["%ty", "ty"]:
 456         d = parse_dates_safe(dates, year=True)
 457         conv_dates = d.year
 458     else:
 459         raise ValueError(f"Format {fmt} is not a known Stata date format")
 460 
 461     conv_dates = Series(conv_dates, dtype=np.float64)
 462     missing_value = struct.unpack("<d", b"\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\xe0\x7f")[0]
 463     conv_dates[bad_loc] = missing_value
 464 
 465     return Series(conv_dates, index=index)

 527 def _cast_to_stata_types(data: DataFrame) -> DataFrame:
 528     """
 529     Checks the dtypes of the columns of a pandas DataFrame for
 530     compatibility with the data types and ranges supported by Stata, and
 531     converts if necessary.
 532 
 533     Parameters
 534     ----------
 535     data : DataFrame
 536         The DataFrame to check and convert
 537 
 538     Notes
 539     -----
 540     Numeric columns in Stata must be one of int8, int16, int32, float32 or
 541     float64, with some additional value restrictions.  int8 and int16 columns
 542     are checked for violations of the value restrictions and upcast if needed.
 543     int64 data is not usable in Stata, and so it is downcast to int32 whenever
 544     the value are in the int32 range, and sidecast to float64 when larger than
 545     this range.  If the int64 values are outside of the range of those
 546     perfectly representable as float64 values, a warning is raised.
 547 
 548     bool columns are cast to int8.  uint columns are converted to int of the
 549     same size if there is no loss in precision, otherwise are upcast to a
 550     larger type.  uint64 is currently not supported since it is concerted to
 551     object in a DataFrame.
 552     """
 553     ws = ""
 554     #                  original, if small, if large
 555     conversion_data = (
 556         (np.bool, np.int8, np.int8),
 557         (np.uint8, np.int8, np.int16),
 558         (np.uint16, np.int16, np.int32),
 559         (np.uint32, np.int32, np.int64),
 560     )
 561 
 562     float32_max = struct.unpack("<f", b"\xff\xff\xff\x7e")[0]
 563     float64_max = struct.unpack("<d", b"\xff\xff\xff\xff\xff\xff\xdf\x7f")[0]
 564 
 565     for col in data:
 566         dtype = data[col].dtype
 567         # Cast from unsupported types to supported types
 568         for c_data in conversion_data:
 569             if dtype == c_data[0]:
 570                 if data[col].max() <= np.iinfo(c_data[1]).max:
 571                     dtype = c_data[1]
 572                 else:
 573                     dtype = c_data[2]
 574                 if c_data[2] == np.float64:  # Warn if necessary
 575                     if data[col].max() >= 2 ** 53:
 576                         ws = precision_loss_doc.format("uint64", "float64")
 577 
 578                 data[col] = data[col].astype(dtype)
 579 
 580         # Check values and upcast if necessary
 581         if dtype == np.int8:
 582             if data[col].max() > 100 or data[col].min() < -127:
 583                 data[col] = data[col].astype(np.int16)
 584         elif dtype == np.int16:
 585             if data[col].max() > 32740 or data[col].min() < -32767:
 586                 data[col] = data[col].astype(np.int32)
 587         elif dtype == np.int64:
 588             if data[col].max() <= 2147483620 and data[col].min() >= -2147483647:
 589                 data[col] = data[col].astype(np.int32)
 590             else:
 591                 data[col] = data[col].astype(np.float64)
 592                 if data[col].max() >= 2 ** 53 or data[col].min() <= -(2 ** 53):
 593                     ws = precision_loss_doc.format("int64", "float64")
 594         elif dtype in (np.float32, np.float64):
 595             value = data[col].max()
 596             if np.isinf(value):
 597                 raise ValueError(
 598                     f"Column {col} has a maximum value of infinity which is outside "
 599                     "the range supported by Stata."
 600                 )
 601             if dtype == np.float32 and value > float32_max:
 602                 data[col] = data[col].astype(np.float64)
 603             elif dtype == np.float64:
 604                 if value > float64_max:
 605                     raise ValueError(
 606                         f"Column {col} has a maximum value ({value}) outside the range "
 607                         f"supported by Stata ({float64_max})"
 608                     )
 609 
 610     if ws:
 611         warnings.warn(ws, PossiblePrecisionLoss)
 612 
 613     return data

 616 class StataValueLabel:
 617     """
 618     Parse a categorical column and prepare formatted output
 619 
 620     Parameters
 621     ----------
 622     catarray : Series
 623         Categorical Series to encode
 624     encoding : {"latin-1", "utf-8"}
 625         Encoding to use for value labels.
 626     """
 627 
 628     def __init__(self, catarray: Series, encoding: str = "latin-1"):
 629 
 630         if encoding not in ("latin-1", "utf-8"):
 631             raise ValueError("Only latin-1 and utf-8 are supported.")
 632         self.labname = catarray.name
 633         self._encoding = encoding
 634         categories = catarray.cat.categories
 635         self.value_labels = list(zip(np.arange(len(categories)), categories))
 636         self.value_labels.sort(key=lambda x: x[0])
 637         self.text_len = 0
 638         self.off: List[int] = []
 639         self.val: List[int] = []
 640         self.txt: List[bytes] = []
 641         self.n = 0
 642 
 643         # Compute lengths and setup lists of offsets and labels
 644         for vl in self.value_labels:
 645             category = vl[1]
 646             if not isinstance(category, str):
 647                 category = str(category)
 648                 warnings.warn(
 649                     value_label_mismatch_doc.format(catarray.name),
 650                     ValueLabelTypeMismatch,
 651                 )
 652             category = category.encode(encoding)
 653             self.off.append(self.text_len)
 654             self.text_len += len(category) + 1  # +1 for the padding
 655             self.val.append(vl[0])
 656             self.txt.append(category)
 657             self.n += 1
 658 
 659         if self.text_len > 32000:
 660             raise ValueError(
 661                 "Stata value labels for a single variable must "
 662                 "have a combined length less than 32,000 characters."
 663             )
 664 
 665         # Ensure int32
 666         self.off = np.array(self.off, dtype=np.int32)
 667         self.val = np.array(self.val, dtype=np.int32)
 668 
 669         # Total length
 670         self.len = 4 + 4 + 4 * self.n + 4 * self.n + self.text_len
 671 
 672     def generate_value_label(self, byteorder: str) -> bytes:
 673         """
 674         Generate the binary representation of the value labels.
 675 
 676         Parameters
 677         ----------
 678         byteorder : str
 679             Byte order of the output
 680 
 681         Returns
 682         -------
 683         value_label : bytes
 684             Bytes containing the formatted value label
 685         """
 686         encoding = self._encoding
 687         bio = BytesIO()
 688         null_byte = b"\x00"
 689 
 690         # len
 691         bio.write(struct.pack(byteorder + "i", self.len))
 692 
 693         # labname
 694         labname = str(self.labname)[:32].encode(encoding)
 695         lab_len = 32 if encoding not in ("utf-8", "utf8") else 128
 696         labname = _pad_bytes(labname, lab_len + 1)
 697         bio.write(labname)
 698 
 699         # padding - 3 bytes
 700         for i in range(3):
 701             bio.write(struct.pack("c", null_byte))
 702 
 703         # value_label_table
 704         # n - int32
 705         bio.write(struct.pack(byteorder + "i", self.n))
 706 
 707         # textlen  - int32
 708         bio.write(struct.pack(byteorder + "i", self.text_len))
 709 
 710         # off - int32 array (n elements)
 711         for offset in self.off:
 712             bio.write(struct.pack(byteorder + "i", offset))
 713 
 714         # val - int32 array (n elements)
 715         for value in self.val:
 716             bio.write(struct.pack(byteorder + "i", value))
 717 
 718         # txt - Text labels, null terminated
 719         for text in self.txt:
 720             bio.write(text + null_byte)
 721 
 722         bio.seek(0)
 723         return bio.read()

 726 class StataMissingValue:
 727     """
 728     An observation's missing value.
 729 
 730     Parameters
 731     ----------
 732     value : {int, float}
 733         The Stata missing value code
 734 
 735     Notes
 736     -----
 737     More information: <https://www.stata.com/help.cgi?missing>
 738 
 739     Integer missing values make the code '.', '.a', ..., '.z' to the ranges
 740     101 ... 127 (for int8), 32741 ... 32767  (for int16) and 2147483621 ...
 741     2147483647 (for int32).  Missing values for floating point data types are
 742     more complex but the pattern is simple to discern from the following table.
 743 
 744     np.float32 missing values (float in Stata)
 745     0000007f    .
 746     0008007f    .a
 747     0010007f    .b
 748     ...
 749     00c0007f    .x
 750     00c8007f    .y
 751     00d0007f    .z
 752 
 753     np.float64 missing values (double in Stata)
 754     000000000000e07f    .
 755     000000000001e07f    .a
 756     000000000002e07f    .b
 757     ...
 758     000000000018e07f    .x
 759     000000000019e07f    .y
 760     00000000001ae07f    .z
 761     """
 762 
 763     # Construct a dictionary of missing values
 764     MISSING_VALUES: Dict[float, str] = {}
 765     bases = (101, 32741, 2147483621)
 766     for b in bases:
 767         # Conversion to long to avoid hash issues on 32 bit platforms #8968
 768         MISSING_VALUES[b] = "."
 769         for i in range(1, 27):
 770             MISSING_VALUES[i + b] = "." + chr(96 + i)
 771 
 772     float32_base = b"\x00\x00\x00\x7f"
 773     increment = struct.unpack("<i", b"\x00\x08\x00\x00")[0]
 774     for i in range(27):
 775         key = struct.unpack("<f", float32_base)[0]
 776         MISSING_VALUES[key] = "."
 777         if i > 0:
 778             MISSING_VALUES[key] += chr(96 + i)
 779         int_value = struct.unpack("<i", struct.pack("<f", key))[0] + increment
 780         float32_base = struct.pack("<i", int_value)
 781 
 782     float64_base = b"\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\xe0\x7f"
 783     increment = struct.unpack("q", b"\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00")[0]
 784     for i in range(27):
 785         key = struct.unpack("<d", float64_base)[0]
 786         MISSING_VALUES[key] = "."
 787         if i > 0:
 788             MISSING_VALUES[key] += chr(96 + i)
 789         int_value = struct.unpack("q", struct.pack("<d", key))[0] + increment
 790         float64_base = struct.pack("q", int_value)
 791 
 792     BASE_MISSING_VALUES = {
 793         "int8": 101,
 794         "int16": 32741,
 795         "int32": 2147483621,
 796         "float32": struct.unpack("<f", float32_base)[0],
 797         "float64": struct.unpack("<d", float64_base)[0],
 798     }
 799 
 800     def __init__(self, value: Union[int, float]):
 801         self._value = value
 802         # Conversion to int to avoid hash issues on 32 bit platforms #8968
 803         value = int(value) if value < 2147483648 else float(value)
 804         self._str = self.MISSING_VALUES[value]
 805 
 806     @property
 807     def string(self) -> str:
 808         """
 809         The Stata representation of the missing value: '.', '.a'..'.z'
 810 
 811         Returns
 812         -------
 813         str
 814             The representation of the missing value.
 815         """
 816         return self._str
 817 
 818     @property
 819     def value(self) -> Union[int, float]:
 820         """
 821         The binary representation of the missing value.
 822 
 823         Returns
 824         -------
 825         {int, float}
 826             The binary representation of the missing value.
 827         """
 828         return self._value
 829 
 830     def __str__(self) -> str:
 831         return self.string
 832 
 833     def __repr__(self) -> str:
 834         return f"{type(self)}({self})"
 835 
 836     def __eq__(self, other: Any) -> bool:
 837         return (
 838             isinstance(other, type(self))
 839             and self.string == other.string
 840             and self.value == other.value
 841         )
 842 
 843     @classmethod
 844     def get_base_missing_value(cls, dtype: np.dtype) -> Union[int, float]:
 845         if dtype == np.int8:
 846             value = cls.BASE_MISSING_VALUES["int8"]
 847         elif dtype == np.int16:
 848             value = cls.BASE_MISSING_VALUES["int16"]
 849         elif dtype == np.int32:
 850             value = cls.BASE_MISSING_VALUES["int32"]
 851         elif dtype == np.float32:
 852             value = cls.BASE_MISSING_VALUES["float32"]
 853         elif dtype == np.float64:
 854             value = cls.BASE_MISSING_VALUES["float64"]
 855         else:
 856             raise ValueError("Unsupported dtype")
 857         return value

1098     def _set_encoding(self) -> None:
1099         """
1100         Set string encoding which depends on file version
1101         """
1102         if self.format_version < 118:
1103             self._encoding = "latin-1"
1104         else:
1105             self._encoding = "utf-8"
1106 
1107     def _read_header(self) -> None:
1108         first_char = self.path_or_buf.read(1)
1109         if struct.unpack("c", first_char)[0] == b"<":
1110             self._read_new_header()
1111         else:
1112             self._read_old_header(first_char)
1113 
1114         self.has_string_data = len([x for x in self.typlist if type(x) is int]) > 0
1115 
1116         # calculate size of a data record
1117         self.col_sizes = [self._calcsize(typ) for typ in self.typlist]
1118 
1119     def _read_new_header(self) -> None:
1120         # The first part of the header is common to 117 - 119.
1121         self.path_or_buf.read(27)  # stata_dta><header><release>
1122         self.format_version = int(self.path_or_buf.read(3))
1123         if self.format_version not in [117, 118, 119]:
1124             raise ValueError(_version_error.format(version=self.format_version))
1125         self._set_encoding()
1126         self.path_or_buf.read(21)  # </release><byteorder>
1127         self.byteorder = self.path_or_buf.read(3) == b"MSF" and ">" or "<"
1128         self.path_or_buf.read(15)  # </byteorder><K>
1129         nvar_type = "H" if self.format_version <= 118 else "I"
1130         nvar_size = 2 if self.format_version <= 118 else 4
1131         self.nvar = struct.unpack(
1132             self.byteorder + nvar_type, self.path_or_buf.read(nvar_size)
1133         )[0]
1134         self.path_or_buf.read(7)  # </K><N>
1135 
1136         self.nobs = self._get_nobs()
1137         self.path_or_buf.read(11)  # </N><label>
1138         self._data_label = self._get_data_label()
1139         self.path_or_buf.read(19)  # </label><timestamp>
1140         self.time_stamp = self._get_time_stamp()
1141         self.path_or_buf.read(26)  # </timestamp></header><map>
1142         self.path_or_buf.read(8)  # 0x0000000000000000
1143         self.path_or_buf.read(8)  # position of <map>
1144 
1145         self._seek_vartypes = (
1146             struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "q", self.path_or_buf.read(8))[0] + 16
1147         )
1148         self._seek_varnames = (
1149             struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "q", self.path_or_buf.read(8))[0] + 10
1150         )
1151         self._seek_sortlist = (
1152             struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "q", self.path_or_buf.read(8))[0] + 10
1153         )
1154         self._seek_formats = (
1155             struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "q", self.path_or_buf.read(8))[0] + 9
1156         )
1157         self._seek_value_label_names = (
1158             struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "q", self.path_or_buf.read(8))[0] + 19
1159         )
1160 
1161         # Requires version-specific treatment
1162         self._seek_variable_labels = self._get_seek_variable_labels()
1163 
1164         self.path_or_buf.read(8)  # <characteristics>
1165         self.data_location = (
1166             struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "q", self.path_or_buf.read(8))[0] + 6
1167         )
1168         self.seek_strls = (
1169             struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "q", self.path_or_buf.read(8))[0] + 7
1170         )
1171         self.seek_value_labels = (
1172             struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "q", self.path_or_buf.read(8))[0] + 14
1173         )
1174 
1175         self.typlist, self.dtyplist = self._get_dtypes(self._seek_vartypes)
1176 
1177         self.path_or_buf.seek(self._seek_varnames)
1178         self.varlist = self._get_varlist()
1179 
1180         self.path_or_buf.seek(self._seek_sortlist)
1181         self.srtlist = struct.unpack(
1182             self.byteorder + ("h" * (self.nvar + 1)),
1183             self.path_or_buf.read(2 * (self.nvar + 1)),
1184         )[:-1]
1185 
1186         self.path_or_buf.seek(self._seek_formats)
1187         self.fmtlist = self._get_fmtlist()
1188 
1189         self.path_or_buf.seek(self._seek_value_label_names)
1190         self.lbllist = self._get_lbllist()
1191 
1192         self.path_or_buf.seek(self._seek_variable_labels)
1193         self._variable_labels = self._get_variable_labels()

1195     # Get data type information, works for versions 117-119.
1196     def _get_dtypes(
1197         self, seek_vartypes: int
1198     ) -> Tuple[List[Union[int, str]], List[Union[int, np.dtype]]]:
1199 
1200         self.path_or_buf.seek(seek_vartypes)
1201         raw_typlist = [
1202             struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "H", self.path_or_buf.read(2))[0]
1203             for _ in range(self.nvar)
1204         ]
1205 
1206         def f(typ: int) -> Union[int, str]:
1207             if typ <= 2045:
1208                 return typ
1209             try:
1210                 return self.TYPE_MAP_XML[typ]
1211             except KeyError as err:
1212                 raise ValueError(f"cannot convert stata types [{typ}]") from err
1213 
1214         typlist = [f(x) for x in raw_typlist]
1215 
1216         def g(typ: int) -> Union[str, np.dtype]:
1217             if typ <= 2045:
1218                 return str(typ)
1219             try:
1220                 return self.DTYPE_MAP_XML[typ]
1221             except KeyError as err:
1222                 raise ValueError(f"cannot convert stata dtype [{typ}]") from err
1223 
1224         dtyplist = [g(x) for x in raw_typlist]
1225 
1226         return typlist, dtyplist

1228     def _get_varlist(self) -> List[str]:
1229         # 33 in order formats, 129 in formats 118 and 119
1230         b = 33 if self.format_version < 118 else 129
1231         return [self._decode(self.path_or_buf.read(b)) for _ in range(self.nvar)]

1240             b = 12

1301     def _get_seek_variable_labels(self) -> int:
1302         if self.format_version == 117:
1303             self.path_or_buf.read(8)  # <variable_labels>, throw away
1304             # Stata 117 data files do not follow the described format.  This is
1305             # a work around that uses the previous label, 33 bytes for each
1306             # variable, 20 for the closing tag and 17 for the opening tag
1307             return self._seek_value_label_names + (33 * self.nvar) + 20 + 17
1308         elif self.format_version >= 118:
1309             return struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "q", self.path_or_buf.read(8))[0] + 17
1310         else:
1311             raise ValueError()

1313     def _read_old_header(self, first_char: bytes) -> None:
1314         self.format_version = struct.unpack("b", first_char)[0]
1315         if self.format_version not in [104, 105, 108, 111, 113, 114, 115]:
1316             raise ValueError(_version_error.format(version=self.format_version))
1317         self._set_encoding()
1318         self.byteorder = (
1319             struct.unpack("b", self.path_or_buf.read(1))[0] == 0x1 and ">" or "<"
1320         )
1321         self.filetype = struct.unpack("b", self.path_or_buf.read(1))[0]
1322         self.path_or_buf.read(1)  # unused
1323 
1324         self.nvar = struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "H", self.path_or_buf.read(2))[0]
1325         self.nobs = self._get_nobs()
1326 
1327         self._data_label = self._get_data_label()
1328 
1329         self.time_stamp = self._get_time_stamp()
1330 
1331         # descriptors
1332         if self.format_version > 108:
1333             typlist = [ord(self.path_or_buf.read(1)) for _ in range(self.nvar)]
1334         else:
1335             buf = self.path_or_buf.read(self.nvar)
1336             typlistb = np.frombuffer(buf, dtype=np.uint8)
1337             typlist = []
1338             for tp in typlistb:
1339                 if tp in self.OLD_TYPE_MAPPING:
1340                     typlist.append(self.OLD_TYPE_MAPPING[tp])
1341                 else:
1342                     typlist.append(tp - 127)  # bytes
1343 
1344         try:
1345             self.typlist = [self.TYPE_MAP[typ] for typ in typlist]
1346         except ValueError as err:
1347             invalid_types = ",".join(str(x) for x in typlist)
1348             raise ValueError(f"cannot convert stata types [{invalid_types}]") from err
1349         try:
1350             self.dtyplist = [self.DTYPE_MAP[typ] for typ in typlist]
1351         except ValueError as err:
1352             invalid_dtypes = ",".join(str(x) for x in typlist)
1353             raise ValueError(f"cannot convert stata dtypes [{invalid_dtypes}]") from err
1354 
1355         if self.format_version > 108:
1356             self.varlist = [
1357                 self._decode(self.path_or_buf.read(33)) for _ in range(self.nvar)
1358             ]
1359         else:
1360             self.varlist = [
1361                 self._decode(self.path_or_buf.read(9)) for _ in range(self.nvar)
1362             ]
1363         self.srtlist = struct.unpack(
1364             self.byteorder + ("h" * (self.nvar + 1)),
1365             self.path_or_buf.read(2 * (self.nvar + 1)),
1366         )[:-1]
1367 
1368         self.fmtlist = self._get_fmtlist()
1369 
1370         self.lbllist = self._get_lbllist()
1371 
1372         self._variable_labels = self._get_variable_labels()
1373 
1374         # ignore expansion fields (Format 105 and later)
1375         # When reading, read five bytes; the last four bytes now tell you
1376         # the size of the next read, which you discard.  You then continue
1377         # like this until you read 5 bytes of zeros.
1378 
1379         if self.format_version > 104:
1380             while True:
1381                 data_type = struct.unpack(
1382                     self.byteorder + "b", self.path_or_buf.read(1)
1383                 )[0]
1384                 if self.format_version > 108:
1385                     data_len = struct.unpack(
1386                         self.byteorder + "i", self.path_or_buf.read(4)
1387                     )[0]
1388                 else:
1389                     data_len = struct.unpack(
1390                         self.byteorder + "h", self.path_or_buf.read(2)
1391                     )[0]
1392                 if data_type == 0:
1393                     break
1394                 self.path_or_buf.read(data_len)
1395 
1396         # necessary data to continue parsing
1397         self.data_location = self.path_or_buf.tell()
1398 
1399     def _setup_dtype(self) -> np.dtype:
1400         """Map between numpy and state dtypes"""
1401         if self._dtype is not None:
1402             return self._dtype
1403 
1404         dtypes = []  # Convert struct data types to numpy data type
1405         for i, typ in enumerate(self.typlist):
1406             if typ in self.NUMPY_TYPE_MAP:
1407                 dtypes.append(("s" + str(i), self.byteorder + self.NUMPY_TYPE_MAP[typ]))
1408             else:
1409                 dtypes.append(("s" + str(i), "S" + str(typ)))
1410         self._dtype = np.dtype(dtypes)
1411 
1412         return self._dtype
1413 
1414     def _calcsize(self, fmt: Union[int, str]) -> int:
1415         if isinstance(fmt, int):
1416             return fmt
1417         return struct.calcsize(self.byteorder + fmt)

1419     def _decode(self, s: bytes) -> str:
1420         # have bytes not strings, so must decode
1421         s = s.partition(b"\0")[0]
1422         try:
1423             return s.decode(self._encoding)
1424         except UnicodeDecodeError:
1425             # GH 25960, fallback to handle incorrect format produced when 117
1426             # files are converted to 118 files in Stata
1427             encoding = self._encoding
1428             msg = f"""
1429 One or more strings in the dta file could not be decoded using {encoding}, and
1430 so the fallback encoding of latin-1 is being used.  This can happen when a file
1431 has been incorrectly encoded by Stata or some other software. You should verify
1432 the string values returned are correct."""
1433             warnings.warn(msg, UnicodeWarning)
1434             return s.decode("latin-1")
1435 
1436     def _read_value_labels(self) -> None:
1437         if self._value_labels_read:
1438             # Don't read twice
1439             return
1440         if self.format_version <= 108:
1441             # Value labels are not supported in version 108 and earlier.
1442             self._value_labels_read = True
1443             self.value_label_dict: Dict[str, Dict[Union[float, int], str]] = {}
1444             return
1445 
1446         if self.format_version >= 117:
1447             self.path_or_buf.seek(self.seek_value_labels)
1448         else:
1449             assert self._dtype is not None
1450             offset = self.nobs * self._dtype.itemsize
1451             self.path_or_buf.seek(self.data_location + offset)
1452 
1453         self._value_labels_read = True
1454         self.value_label_dict = {}
1455 
1456         while True:
1457             if self.format_version >= 117:
1458                 if self.path_or_buf.read(5) == b"</val":  # <lbl>
1459                     break  # end of value label table
1460 
1461             slength = self.path_or_buf.read(4)
1462             if not slength:
1463                 break  # end of value label table (format < 117)
1464             if self.format_version <= 117:
1465                 labname = self._decode(self.path_or_buf.read(33))
1466             else:
1467                 labname = self._decode(self.path_or_buf.read(129))
1468             self.path_or_buf.read(3)  # padding
1469 
1470             n = struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "I", self.path_or_buf.read(4))[0]
1471             txtlen = struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "I", self.path_or_buf.read(4))[0]
1472             off = np.frombuffer(
1473                 self.path_or_buf.read(4 * n), dtype=self.byteorder + "i4", count=n
1474             )
1475             val = np.frombuffer(
1476                 self.path_or_buf.read(4 * n), dtype=self.byteorder + "i4", count=n
1477             )
1478             ii = np.argsort(off)
1479             off = off[ii]
1480             val = val[ii]
1481             txt = self.path_or_buf.read(txtlen)
1482             self.value_label_dict[labname] = dict()
1483             for i in range(n):
1484                 end = off[i + 1] if i < n - 1 else txtlen
1485                 self.value_label_dict[labname][val[i]] = self._decode(txt[off[i] : end])
1486             if self.format_version >= 117:
1487                 self.path_or_buf.read(6)  # </lbl>
1488         self._value_labels_read = True
1489 
1490     def _read_strls(self) -> None:
1491         self.path_or_buf.seek(self.seek_strls)
1492         # Wrap v_o in a string to allow uint64 values as keys on 32bit OS
1493         self.GSO = {"0": ""}
1494         while True:
1495             if self.path_or_buf.read(3) != b"GSO":
1496                 break
1497 
1498             if self.format_version == 117:
1499                 v_o = struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "Q", self.path_or_buf.read(8))[0]
1500             else:
1501                 buf = self.path_or_buf.read(12)
1502                 # Only tested on little endian file on little endian machine.
1503                 v_size = 2 if self.format_version == 118 else 3
1504                 if self.byteorder == "<":
1505                     buf = buf[0:v_size] + buf[4 : (12 - v_size)]
1506                 else:
1507                     # This path may not be correct, impossible to test
1508                     buf = buf[0:v_size] + buf[(4 + v_size) :]
1509                 v_o = struct.unpack("Q", buf)[0]
1510             typ = struct.unpack("B", self.path_or_buf.read(1))[0]
1511             length = struct.unpack(self.byteorder + "I", self.path_or_buf.read(4))[0]
1512             va = self.path_or_buf.read(length)
1513             if typ == 130:
1514                 decoded_va = va[0:-1].decode(self._encoding)
1515             else:
1516                 # Stata says typ 129 can be binary, so use str
1517                 decoded_va = str(va)
1518                 # Wrap v_o in a string to allow uint64 values as keys on 32bit OS
1519             self.GSO[str(v_o)] = decoded_va
1520 
1521     def __next__(self) -> DataFrame:
1522         if self._chunksize is None:
1523             raise ValueError(
1524                 "chunksize must be set to a positive integer to use as an iterator."
1525             )
1526         return self.read(nrows=self._chunksize or 1)

1528     def get_chunk(self, size: Optional[int] = None) -> DataFrame:
1529         """
1530         Reads lines from Stata file and returns as dataframe
1531 
1532         Parameters
1533         ----------
1534         size : int, defaults to None
1535             Number of lines to read.  If None, reads whole file.
1536 
1537         Returns
1538         -------
1539         DataFrame
1540         """
1541         if size is None:
1542             size = self._chunksize
1543         return self.read(nrows=size)

1545     @Appender(_read_method_doc)
1546     def read(
1547         self,
1548         nrows: Optional[int] = None,
1549         convert_dates: Optional[bool] = None,
1550         convert_categoricals: Optional[bool] = None,
1551         index_col: Optional[str] = None,
1552         convert_missing: Optional[bool] = None,
1553         preserve_dtypes: Optional[bool] = None,
1554         columns: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
1555         order_categoricals: Optional[bool] = None,
1556     ) -> DataFrame:
1557         # Handle empty file or chunk.  If reading incrementally raise
1558         # StopIteration.  If reading the whole thing return an empty
1559         # data frame.
1560         if (self.nobs == 0) and (nrows is None):
1561             self._can_read_value_labels = True
1562             self._data_read = True
1563             self.close()
1564             return DataFrame(columns=self.varlist)
1565 
1566         # Handle options
1567         if convert_dates is None:
1568             convert_dates = self._convert_dates
1569         if convert_categoricals is None:
1570             convert_categoricals = self._convert_categoricals
1571         if convert_missing is None:
1572             convert_missing = self._convert_missing
1573         if preserve_dtypes is None:
1574             preserve_dtypes = self._preserve_dtypes
1575         if columns is None:
1576             columns = self._columns
1577         if order_categoricals is None:
1578             order_categoricals = self._order_categoricals
1579         if index_col is None:
1580             index_col = self._index_col
1581 
1582         if nrows is None:
1583             nrows = self.nobs
1584 
1585         if (self.format_version >= 117) and (not self._value_labels_read):
1586             self._can_read_value_labels = True
1587             self._read_strls()
1588 
1589         # Read data
1590         assert self._dtype is not None
1591         dtype = self._dtype
1592         max_read_len = (self.nobs - self._lines_read) * dtype.itemsize
1593         read_len = nrows * dtype.itemsize
1594         read_len = min(read_len, max_read_len)
1595         if read_len <= 0:
1596             # Iterator has finished, should never be here unless
1597             # we are reading the file incrementally
1598             if convert_categoricals:
1599                 self._read_value_labels()
1600             self.close()
1601             raise StopIteration
1602         offset = self._lines_read * dtype.itemsize
1603         self.path_or_buf.seek(self.data_location + offset)
1604         read_lines = min(nrows, self.nobs - self._lines_read)
1605         data = np.frombuffer(
1606             self.path_or_buf.read(read_len), dtype=dtype, count=read_lines
1607         )
1608 
1609         self._lines_read += read_lines
1610         if self._lines_read == self.nobs:
1611             self._can_read_value_labels = True
1612             self._data_read = True
1613         # if necessary, swap the byte order to native here
1614         if self.byteorder != self._native_byteorder:
1615             data = data.byteswap().newbyteorder()
1616 
1617         if convert_categoricals:
1618             self._read_value_labels()
1619 
1620         if len(data) == 0:
1621             data = DataFrame(columns=self.varlist)
1622         else:
1623             data = DataFrame.from_records(data)
1624             data.columns = self.varlist
1625 
1626         # If index is not specified, use actual row number rather than
1627         # restarting at 0 for each chunk.
1628         if index_col is None:
1629             ix = np.arange(self._lines_read - read_lines, self._lines_read)
1630             data = data.set_index(ix)
1631 
1632         if columns is not None:
1633             try:
1634                 data = self._do_select_columns(data, columns)
1635             except ValueError:
1636                 self.close()
1637                 raise
1638 
1639         # Decode strings
1640         for col, typ in zip(data, self.typlist):
1641             if type(typ) is int:
1642                 data[col] = data[col].apply(self._decode, convert_dtype=True)
1643 
1644         data = self._insert_strls(data)
1645 
1646         cols_ = np.where(self.dtyplist)[0]
1647 
1648         # Convert columns (if needed) to match input type
1649         ix = data.index
1650         requires_type_conversion = False
1651         data_formatted = []
1652         for i in cols_:
1653             if self.dtyplist[i] is not None:
1654                 col = data.columns[i]
1655                 dtype = data[col].dtype
1656                 if dtype != np.dtype(object) and dtype != self.dtyplist[i]:
1657                     requires_type_conversion = True
1658                     data_formatted.append(
1659                         (col, Series(data[col], ix, self.dtyplist[i]))
1660                     )
1661                 else:
1662                     data_formatted.append((col, data[col]))
1663         if requires_type_conversion:
1664             data = DataFrame.from_dict(dict(data_formatted))
1665         del data_formatted
1666 
1667         data = self._do_convert_missing(data, convert_missing)
1668 
1669         if convert_dates:
1670 
1671             def any_startswith(x: str) -> bool:
1672                 return any(x.startswith(fmt) for fmt in _date_formats)
1673 
1674             cols = np.where([any_startswith(x) for x in self.fmtlist])[0]
1675             for i in cols:
1676                 col = data.columns[i]
1677                 try:
1678                     data[col] = _stata_elapsed_date_to_datetime_vec(
1679                         data[col], self.fmtlist[i]
1680                     )
1681                 except ValueError:
1682                     self.close()
1683                     raise
1684 
1685         if convert_categoricals and self.format_version > 108:
1686             data = self._do_convert_categoricals(
1687                 data, self.value_label_dict, self.lbllist, order_categoricals
1688             )
1689 
1690         if not preserve_dtypes:
1691             retyped_data = []
1692             convert = False
1693             for col in data:
1694                 dtype = data[col].dtype
1695                 if dtype in (np.float16, np.float32):
1696                     dtype = np.float64
1697                     convert = True
1698                 elif dtype in (np.int8, np.int16, np.int32):
1699                     dtype = np.int64
1700                     convert = True
1701                 retyped_data.append((col, data[col].astype(dtype)))
1702             if convert:
1703                 data = DataFrame.from_dict(dict(retyped_data))
1704 
1705         if index_col is not None:
1706             data = data.set_index(data.pop(index_col))
1707 
1708         return data
1709 
1710     def _do_convert_missing(self, data: DataFrame, convert_missing: bool) -> DataFrame:
1711         # Check for missing values, and replace if found
1712         replacements = {}
1713         for i, colname in enumerate(data):
1714             fmt = self.typlist[i]
1715             if fmt not in self.VALID_RANGE:
1716                 continue
1717 
1718             nmin, nmax = self.VALID_RANGE[fmt]
1719             series = data[colname]
1720             missing = np.logical_or(series < nmin, series > nmax)
1721 
1722             if not missing.any():
1723                 continue
1724 
1725             if convert_missing:  # Replacement follows Stata notation
1726                 missing_loc = np.nonzero(np.asarray(missing))[0]
1727                 umissing, umissing_loc = np.unique(series[missing], return_inverse=True)
1728                 replacement = Series(series, dtype=np.object)
1729                 for j, um in enumerate(umissing):
1730                     missing_value = StataMissingValue(um)
1731 
1732                     loc = missing_loc[umissing_loc == j]
1733                     replacement.iloc[loc] = missing_value
1734             else:  # All replacements are identical
1735                 dtype = series.dtype
1736                 if dtype not in (np.float32, np.float64):
1737                     dtype = np.float64
1738                 replacement = Series(series, dtype=dtype)
1739                 replacement[missing] = np.nan
1740             replacements[colname] = replacement
1741         if replacements:
1742             columns = data.columns
1743             replacement_df = DataFrame(replacements)
1744             replaced = concat([data.drop(replacement_df.columns, 1), replacement_df], 1)
1745             data = replaced[columns]
1746         return data

1748     def _insert_strls(self, data: DataFrame) -> DataFrame:
1749         if not hasattr(self, "GSO") or len(self.GSO) == 0:
1750             return data
1751         for i, typ in enumerate(self.typlist):
1752             if typ != "Q":
1753                 continue
1754             # Wrap v_o in a string to allow uint64 values as keys on 32bit OS
1755             data.iloc[:, i] = [self.GSO[str(k)] for k in data.iloc[:, i]]
1756         return data

1758     def _do_select_columns(self, data: DataFrame, columns: Sequence[str]) -> DataFrame:
1759 
1760         if not self._column_selector_set:
1761             column_set = set(columns)
1762             if len(column_set) != len(columns):
1763                 raise ValueError("columns contains duplicate entries")
1764             unmatched = column_set.difference(data.columns)
1765             if unmatched:
1766                 joined = ", ".join(list(unmatched))
1767                 raise ValueError(
1768                     "The following columns were not "
1769                     f"found in the Stata data set: {joined}"
1770                 )
1771             # Copy information for retained columns for later processing
1772             dtyplist = []
1773             typlist = []
1774             fmtlist = []
1775             lbllist = []
1776             for col in columns:
1777                 i = data.columns.get_loc(col)
1778                 dtyplist.append(self.dtyplist[i])
1779                 typlist.append(self.typlist[i])
1780                 fmtlist.append(self.fmtlist[i])
1781                 lbllist.append(self.lbllist[i])
1782 
1783             self.dtyplist = dtyplist
1784             self.typlist = typlist
1785             self.fmtlist = fmtlist
1786             self.lbllist = lbllist
1787             self._column_selector_set = True
1788 
1789         return data[columns]

1791     def _do_convert_categoricals(
1792         self,
1793         data: DataFrame,
1794         value_label_dict: Dict[str, Dict[Union[float, int], str]],
1795         lbllist: Sequence[str],
1796         order_categoricals: bool,
1797     ) -> DataFrame:
1798         """
1799         Converts categorical columns to Categorical type.
1800         """
1801         value_labels = list(value_label_dict.keys())
1802         cat_converted_data = []
1803         for col, label in zip(data, lbllist):
1804             if label in value_labels:
1805                 # Explicit call with ordered=True
1806                 vl = value_label_dict[label]
1807                 keys = np.array(list(vl.keys()))
1808                 column = data[col]
1809                 key_matches = column.isin(keys)
1810                 if self._chunksize is not None and key_matches.all():
1811                     initial_categories = keys
1812                     # If all categories are in the keys and we are iterating,
1813                     # use the same keys for all chunks. If some are missing
1814                     # value labels, then we will fall back to the categories
1815                     # varying across chunks.
1816                 else:
1817                     if self._chunksize is not None:
1818                         # warn is using an iterator
1819                         warnings.warn(
1820                             categorical_conversion_warning, CategoricalConversionWarning
1821                         )
1822                     initial_categories = None
1823                 cat_data = Categorical(
1824                     column, categories=initial_categories, ordered=order_categoricals
1825                 )
1826                 if initial_categories is None:
1827                     # If None here, then we need to match the cats in the Categorical
1828                     categories = []
1829                     for category in cat_data.categories:
1830                         if category in vl:
1831                             categories.append(vl[category])
1832                         else:
1833                             categories.append(category)
1834                 else:
1835                     # If all cats are matched, we can use the values
1836                     categories = list(vl.values())
1837                 try:
1838                     # Try to catch duplicate categories
1839                     cat_data.categories = categories
1840                 except ValueError as err:
1841                     vc = Series(categories).value_counts()
1842                     repeated_cats = list(vc.index[vc > 1])
1843                     repeats = "-" * 80 + "\n" + "\n".join(repeated_cats)
1844                     # GH 25772
1845                     msg = f"""
1846 Value labels for column {col} are not unique. These cannot be converted to
1847 pandas categoricals.
1848 
1849 Either read the file with `convert_categoricals` set to False or use the
1850 low level interface in `StataReader` to separately read the values and the
1851 value_labels.
1852 
1853 The repeated labels are:
1854 {repeats}
1855 """
1856                     raise ValueError(msg) from err
1857                 # TODO: is the next line needed above in the data(...) method?
1858                 cat_series = Series(cat_data, index=data.index)
1859                 cat_converted_data.append((col, cat_series))
1860             else:
1861                 cat_converted_data.append((col, data[col]))
1862         data = DataFrame.from_dict(dict(cat_converted_data))
1863         return data

1934 def _open_file_binary_write(
1935     fname: FilePathOrBuffer, compression: Union[str, Mapping[str, str], None],
1936 ) -> Tuple[BinaryIO, bool, Optional[Union[str, Mapping[str, str]]]]:
1937     """
1938     Open a binary file or no-op if file-like.
1939 
1940     Parameters
1941     ----------
1942     fname : string path, path object or buffer
1943         The file name or buffer.
1944     compression : {str, dict, None}
1945         The compression method to use.
1946 
1947     Returns
1948     -------
1949     file : file-like object
1950         File object supporting write
1951     own : bool
1952         True if the file was created, otherwise False
1953     """
1954     if hasattr(fname, "write"):
1955         # See https://github.com/python/mypy/issues/1424 for hasattr challenges
1956         return fname, False, None  # type: ignore
1957     elif isinstance(fname, (str, Path)):
1958         # Extract compression mode as given, if dict
1959         compression_typ, compression_args = get_compression_method(compression)
1960         compression_typ = infer_compression(fname, compression_typ)
1961         path_or_buf, _, compression_typ, _ = get_filepath_or_buffer(
1962             fname, compression=compression_typ
1963         )
1964         if compression_typ is not None:
1965             compression = compression_args
1966             compression["method"] = compression_typ
1967         else:
1968             compression = None
1969         f, _ = get_handle(path_or_buf, "wb", compression=compression, is_text=False)
1970         return f, True, compression
1971     else:
1972         raise TypeError("fname must be a binary file, buffer or path-like.")

1975 def _set_endianness(endianness: str) -> str:

1984 def _pad_bytes(name: AnyStr, length: int) -> AnyStr:
1985     """
1986     Take a char string and pads it with null bytes until it's length chars.
1987     """
1988     if isinstance(name, bytes):
1989         return name + b"\x00" * (length - len(name))
1990     return name + "\x00" * (length - len(name))

2018 def _maybe_convert_to_int_keys(convert_dates: Dict, varlist: List[Label]) -> Dict:
2019     new_dict = {}
2020     for key in convert_dates:
2021         if not convert_dates[key].startswith("%"):  # make sure proper fmts
2022             convert_dates[key] = "%" + convert_dates[key]
2023         if key in varlist:
2024             new_dict.update({varlist.index(key): convert_dates[key]})
2025         else:

2032 def _dtype_to_stata_type(dtype: np.dtype, column: Series) -> int:
2033     """
2034     Convert dtype types to stata types. Returns the byte of the given ordinal.
2035     See TYPE_MAP and comments for an explanation. This is also explained in
2036     the dta spec.
2037     1 - 244 are strings of this length
2038                          Pandas    Stata
2039     251 - for int8      byte
2040     252 - for int16     int
2041     253 - for int32     long
2042     254 - for float32   float
2043     255 - for double    double
2044 
2045     If there are dates to convert, then dtype will already have the correct
2046     type inserted.
2047     """
2048     # TODO: expand to handle datetime to integer conversion
2049     if dtype.type == np.object_:  # try to coerce it to the biggest string
2050         # not memory efficient, what else could we
2051         # do?
2052         itemsize = max_len_string_array(ensure_object(column._values))
2053         return max(itemsize, 1)
2054     elif dtype == np.float64:
2055         return 255
2056     elif dtype == np.float32:
2057         return 254
2058     elif dtype == np.int32:
2059         return 253
2060     elif dtype == np.int16:
2061         return 252
2062     elif dtype == np.int8:
2063         return 251
2064     else:  # pragma : no cover
2065         raise NotImplementedError(f"Data type {dtype} not supported.")

2068 def _dtype_to_default_stata_fmt(
2069     dtype, column: Series, dta_version: int = 114, force_strl: bool = False
2070 ) -> str:
2071     """
2072     Map numpy dtype to stata's default format for this type. Not terribly
2073     important since users can change this in Stata. Semantics are
2074 
2075     object  -> "%DDs" where DD is the length of the string.  If not a string,
2076                 raise ValueError
2077     float64 -> "%10.0g"
2078     float32 -> "%9.0g"
2079     int64   -> "%9.0g"
2080     int32   -> "%12.0g"
2081     int16   -> "%8.0g"
2082     int8    -> "%8.0g"
2083     strl    -> "%9s"
2084     """
2085     # TODO: Refactor to combine type with format
2086     # TODO: expand this to handle a default datetime format?
2087     if dta_version < 117:
2088         max_str_len = 244
2089     else:
2090         max_str_len = 2045
2091         if force_strl:
2092             return "%9s"
2093     if dtype.type == np.object_:
2094         itemsize = max_len_string_array(ensure_object(column._values))
2095         if itemsize > max_str_len:
2096             if dta_version >= 117:
2097                 return "%9s"
2098             else:
2099                 raise ValueError(excessive_string_length_error.format(column.name))
2100         return "%" + str(max(itemsize, 1)) + "s"
2101     elif dtype == np.float64:
2102         return "%10.0g"
2103     elif dtype == np.float32:
2104         return "%9.0g"
2105     elif dtype == np.int32:
2106         return "%12.0g"
2107     elif dtype == np.int8 or dtype == np.int16:
2108         return "%8.0g"
2109     else:  # pragma : no cover
2110         raise NotImplementedError(f"Data type {dtype} not supported.")

2113 class StataWriter(StataParser):
2114     """
2115     A class for writing Stata binary dta files
2116 
2117     Parameters
2118     ----------
2119     fname : path (string), buffer or path object
2120         string, path object (pathlib.Path or py._path.local.LocalPath) or
2121         object implementing a binary write() functions. If using a buffer
2122         then the buffer will not be automatically closed after the file
2123         is written.
2124 
2125         .. versionadded:: 0.23.0 support for pathlib, py.path.
2126 
2127     data : DataFrame
2128         Input to save
2129     convert_dates : dict
2130         Dictionary mapping columns containing datetime types to stata internal
2131         format to use when writing the dates. Options are 'tc', 'td', 'tm',
2132         'tw', 'th', 'tq', 'ty'. Column can be either an integer or a name.
2133         Datetime columns that do not have a conversion type specified will be
2134         converted to 'tc'. Raises NotImplementedError if a datetime column has
2135         timezone information
2136     write_index : bool
2137         Write the index to Stata dataset.
2138     byteorder : str
2139         Can be ">", "<", "little", or "big". default is `sys.byteorder`
2140     time_stamp : datetime
2141         A datetime to use as file creation date.  Default is the current time
2142     data_label : str
2143         A label for the data set.  Must be 80 characters or smaller.
2144     variable_labels : dict
2145         Dictionary containing columns as keys and variable labels as values.
2146         Each label must be 80 characters or smaller.
2147     compression : str or dict, default 'infer'
2148         For on-the-fly compression of the output dta. If string, specifies
2149         compression mode. If dict, value at key 'method' specifies compression
2150         mode. Compression mode must be one of {'infer', 'gzip', 'bz2', 'zip',
2151         'xz', None}. If compression mode is 'infer' and `fname` is path-like,
2152         then detect compression from the following extensions: '.gz', '.bz2',
2153         '.zip', or '.xz' (otherwise no compression). If dict and compression
2154         mode is one of {'zip', 'gzip', 'bz2'}, or inferred as one of the above,
2155         other entries passed as additional compression options.
2156 
2157         .. versionadded:: 1.1.0
2158 
2159     Returns
2160     -------
2161     writer : StataWriter instance
2162         The StataWriter instance has a write_file method, which will
2163         write the file to the given `fname`.
2164 
2165     Raises
2166     ------
2167     NotImplementedError
2168         * If datetimes contain timezone information
2169     ValueError
2170         * Columns listed in convert_dates are neither datetime64[ns]
2171           or datetime.datetime
2172         * Column dtype is not representable in Stata
2173         * Column listed in convert_dates is not in DataFrame
2174         * Categorical label contains more than 32,000 characters
2175 
2176     Examples
2177     --------
2178     >>> data = pd.DataFrame([[1.0, 1]], columns=['a', 'b'])
2179     >>> writer = StataWriter('./data_file.dta', data)
2180     >>> writer.write_file()
2181 
2182     Directly write a zip file
2183     >>> compression = {"method": "zip", "archive_name": "data_file.dta"}
2184     >>> writer = StataWriter('./data_file.zip', data, compression=compression)
2185     >>> writer.write_file()
2186 
2187     Save a DataFrame with dates
2188     >>> from datetime import datetime
2189     >>> data = pd.DataFrame([[datetime(2000,1,1)]], columns=['date'])
2190     >>> writer = StataWriter('./date_data_file.dta', data, {'date' : 'tw'})
2191     >>> writer.write_file()
2192     """
2193

2243     def _prepare_categoricals(self, data: DataFrame) -> DataFrame:
2244         """
2245         Check for categorical columns, retain categorical information for
2246         Stata file and convert categorical data to int
2247         """
2248         is_cat = [is_categorical_dtype(data[col].dtype) for col in data]
2249         self._is_col_cat = is_cat
2250         self._value_labels: List[StataValueLabel] = []
2251         if not any(is_cat):
2252             return data
2253 
2254         get_base_missing_value = StataMissingValue.get_base_missing_value
2255         data_formatted = []
2256         for col, col_is_cat in zip(data, is_cat):
2257             if col_is_cat:
2258                 svl = StataValueLabel(data[col], encoding=self._encoding)
2259                 self._value_labels.append(svl)
2260                 dtype = data[col].cat.codes.dtype
2261                 if dtype == np.int64:
2262                     raise ValueError(
2263                         "It is not possible to export "
2264                         "int64-based categorical data to Stata."
2265                     )
2266                 values = data[col].cat.codes._values.copy()
2267 
2268                 # Upcast if needed so that correct missing values can be set
2269                 if values.max() >= get_base_missing_value(dtype):
2270                     if dtype == np.int8:
2271                         dtype = np.int16
2272                     elif dtype == np.int16:
2273                         dtype = np.int32
2274                     else:
2275                         dtype = np.float64
2276                     values = np.array(values, dtype=dtype)
2277 
2278                 # Replace missing values with Stata missing value for type
2279                 values[values == -1] = get_base_missing_value(dtype)
2280                 data_formatted.append((col, values))
2281             else:
2282                 data_formatted.append((col, data[col]))
2283         return DataFrame.from_dict(dict(data_formatted))

2306     def _validate_variable_name(self, name: str) -> str:
2307         """
2308         Validate variable names for Stata export.
2309 
2310         Parameters
2311         ----------
2312         name : str
2313             Variable name
2314 
2315         Returns
2316         -------
2317         str
2318             The validated name with invalid characters replaced with
2319             underscores.
2320 
2321         Notes
2322         -----
2323         Stata 114 and 117 support ascii characters in a-z, A-Z, 0-9
2324         and _.
2325         """
2326         for c in name:
2327             if (
2328                 (c < "A" or c > "Z")
2329                 and (c < "a" or c > "z")
2330                 and (c < "0" or c > "9")
2331                 and c != "_"
2332             ):
2333                 name = name.replace(c, "_")
2334         return name

2336     def _check_column_names(self, data: DataFrame) -> DataFrame:
2337         """
2338         Checks column names to ensure that they are valid Stata column names.
2339         This includes checks for:
2340             * Non-string names
2341             * Stata keywords
2342             * Variables that start with numbers
2343             * Variables with names that are too long
2344 
2345         When an illegal variable name is detected, it is converted, and if
2346         dates are exported, the variable name is propagated to the date
2347         conversion dictionary
2348         """
2349         converted_names: Dict[Label, str] = {}
2350         columns: List[Label] = list(data.columns)
2351         original_columns = columns[:]
2352 
2353         duplicate_var_id = 0
2354         for j, name in enumerate(columns):
2355             orig_name = name
2356             if not isinstance(name, str):
2357                 name = str(name)
2358 
2359             name = self._validate_variable_name(name)
2360 
2361             # Variable name must not be a reserved word
2362             if name in self.RESERVED_WORDS:
2363                 name = "_" + name
2364 
2365             # Variable name may not start with a number
2366             if "0" <= name[0] <= "9":
2367                 name = "_" + name
2368 
2369             name = name[: min(len(name), 32)]
2370 
2371             if not name == orig_name:
2372                 # check for duplicates
2373                 while columns.count(name) > 0:
2374                     # prepend ascending number to avoid duplicates
2375                     name = "_" + str(duplicate_var_id) + name
2376                     name = name[: min(len(name), 32)]
2377                     duplicate_var_id += 1
2378                 converted_names[orig_name] = name
2379 
2380             columns[j] = name
2381 
2382         data.columns = Index(columns)
2383 
2384         # Check date conversion, and fix key if needed
2385         if self._convert_dates:
2386             for c, o in zip(columns, original_columns):
2387                 if c != o:
2388                     self._convert_dates[c] = self._convert_dates[o]
2389                     del self._convert_dates[o]
2390 
2391         if converted_names:
2392             conversion_warning = []
2393             for orig_name, name in converted_names.items():
2394                 msg = f"{orig_name}   ->   {name}"
2395                 conversion_warning.append(msg)
2396 
2397             ws = invalid_name_doc.format("\n    ".join(conversion_warning))
2398             warnings.warn(ws, InvalidColumnName)
2399 
2400         self._converted_names = converted_names
2401         self._update_strl_names()
2402 
2403         return data

2412     def _prepare_pandas(self, data: DataFrame) -> None:
2413         # NOTE: we might need a different API / class for pandas objects so
2414         # we can set different semantics - handle this with a PR to pandas.io
2415 
2416         data = data.copy()
2417 
2418         if self._write_index:
2419             temp = data.reset_index()
2420             if isinstance(temp, DataFrame):
2421                 data = temp
2422 
2423         # Ensure column names are strings
2424         data = self._check_column_names(data)
2425 
2426         # Check columns for compatibility with stata, upcast if necessary
2427         # Raise if outside the supported range
2428         data = _cast_to_stata_types(data)
2429 
2430         # Replace NaNs with Stata missing values
2431         data = self._replace_nans(data)

2434         data = self._prepare_categoricals(data)

2437         self.data = data
2438         self.varlist = data.columns.tolist()

2441 
2442         # Ensure all date columns are converted
2443         for col in data:
2444             if col in self._convert_dates:
2445                 continue
2446             if is_datetime64_dtype(data[col]):
2447                 self._convert_dates[col] = "tc"
2448 
2449         self._convert_dates = _maybe_convert_to_int_keys(
2450             self._convert_dates, self.varlist
2451         )
2452         for key in self._convert_dates:
2453             new_type = _convert_datetime_to_stata_type(self._convert_dates[key])
2454             dtypes[key] = np.dtype(new_type)
2455 
2456         # Verify object arrays are strings and encode to bytes
2457         self._encode_strings()
2458 
2459         self._set_formats_and_types(dtypes)
2460 
2461         # set the given format for the datetime cols
2462         if self._convert_dates is not None:
2463             for key in self._convert_dates:

2467     def _encode_strings(self) -> None:
2468         """
2469         Encode strings in dta-specific encoding
2470 
2471         Do not encode columns marked for date conversion or for strL
2472         conversion. The strL converter independently handles conversion and
2473         also accepts empty string arrays.
2474         """
2475         convert_dates = self._convert_dates
2476         # _convert_strl is not available in dta 114
2477         convert_strl = getattr(self, "_convert_strl", [])
2478         for i, col in enumerate(self.data):
2479             # Skip columns marked for date conversion or strl conversion
2480             if i in convert_dates or col in convert_strl:
2481                 continue
2482             column = self.data[col]
2483             dtype = column.dtype
2484             if dtype.type == np.object_:
2485                 inferred_dtype = infer_dtype(column, skipna=True)
2486                 if not ((inferred_dtype == "string") or len(column) == 0):
2487                     col = column.name
2488                     raise ValueError(
2489                         f"""\
2490 Column `{col}` cannot be exported.\n\nOnly string-like object arrays
2491 containing all strings or a mix of strings and None can be exported.
2492 Object arrays containing only null values are prohibited. Other object
2493 types cannot be exported and must first be converted to one of the
2494 supported types."""
2495                     )
2496                 encoded = self.data[col].str.encode(self._encoding)
2497                 # If larger than _max_string_length do nothing
2498                 if (
2499                     max_len_string_array(ensure_object(encoded._values))
2500                     <= self._max_string_length
2501                 ):
2502                     self.data[col] = encoded

2504     def write_file(self) -> None:
2505         self._file, self._own_file, compression = _open_file_binary_write(
2506             self._fname, self._compression
2507         )
2508         if compression is not None:
2509             self._output_file = self._file
2510             self._file = BytesIO()
2511         try:
2512             self._write_header(data_label=self._data_label, time_stamp=self._time_stamp)
2513             self._write_map()

2531                 try:
2532                     if isinstance(self._fname, (str, Path)):
2533                         os.unlink(self._fname)
2534                 except OSError:
2535                     warnings.warn(
2536                         f"This save was not successful but {self._fname} could not "
2537                         "be deleted.  This file is not valid.",
2538                         ResourceWarning,
2539                     )
2540             raise exc
2541         else:
2542             self._close()

2544     def _close(self) -> None:
2545         """
2546         Close the file if it was created by the writer.
2547 
2548         If a buffer or file-like object was passed in, for example a GzipFile,
2549         then leave this file open for the caller to close. In either case,
2550         attempt to flush the file contents to ensure they are written to disk
2551         (if supported)
2552         """
2553         # Some file-like objects might not support flush
2554         assert self._file is not None
2555         if self._output_file is not None:
2556             assert isinstance(self._file, BytesIO)
2557             bio = self._file
2558             bio.seek(0)
2559             self._file = self._output_file
2560             self._file.write(bio.read())
2561         try:
2562             self._file.flush()
2563         except AttributeError:
2564             pass
2565         if self._own_file:
2566             self._file.close()
