2592     def _write_header(
2593         self,
2594         data_label: Optional[str] = None,
2595         time_stamp: Optional[datetime.datetime] = None,
2596     ) -> None:
2597         byteorder = self._byteorder
2598         # ds_format - just use 114
2599         self._write_bytes(struct.pack("b", 114))
2600         # byteorder
2601         self._write(byteorder == ">" and "\x01" or "\x02")
2602         # filetype
2603         self._write("\x01")
2604         # unused
2605         self._write("\x00")
2606         # number of vars, 2 bytes
2607         self._write_bytes(struct.pack(byteorder + "h", self.nvar)[:2])
2608         # number of obs, 4 bytes
2609         self._write_bytes(struct.pack(byteorder + "i", self.nobs)[:4])
2610         # data label 81 bytes, char, null terminated
2611         if data_label is None:
2612             self._write_bytes(self._null_terminate_bytes(_pad_bytes("", 80)))
2613         else:
2614             self._write_bytes(
2615                 self._null_terminate_bytes(_pad_bytes(data_label[:80], 80))
2616             )
2617         # time stamp, 18 bytes, char, null terminated
2618         # format dd Mon yyyy hh:mm
2619         if time_stamp is None:
2620             time_stamp = datetime.datetime.now()
2621         elif not isinstance(time_stamp, datetime.datetime):
2622             raise ValueError("time_stamp should be datetime type")
2623         # GH #13856
2624         # Avoid locale-specific month conversion
2625         months = [
2626             "Jan",
2627             "Feb",
2628             "Mar",
2629             "Apr",
2630             "May",
2631             "Jun",
2632             "Jul",
2633             "Aug",
2634             "Sep",
2635             "Oct",
2636             "Nov",
2637             "Dec",
2638         ]
2639         month_lookup = {i + 1: month for i, month in enumerate(months)}
2640         ts = (
2641             time_stamp.strftime("%d ")
2642             + month_lookup[time_stamp.month]
2643             + time_stamp.strftime(" %Y %H:%M")
2644         )
2645         self._write_bytes(self._null_terminate_bytes(ts))
2646 
2647     def _write_variable_types(self) -> None:
2648         for typ in self.typlist:
2649             self._write_bytes(struct.pack("B", typ))
2650 
2651     def _write_varnames(self) -> None:
2652         # varlist names are checked by _check_column_names
2653         # varlist, requires null terminated
2654         for name in self.varlist:
2655             name = self._null_terminate_str(name)
2656             name = _pad_bytes(name[:32], 33)
2657             self._write(name)
2658 
2659     def _write_sortlist(self) -> None:
2660         # srtlist, 2*(nvar+1), int array, encoded by byteorder
2661         srtlist = _pad_bytes("", 2 * (self.nvar + 1))
2662         self._write(srtlist)
2663 
2664     def _write_formats(self) -> None:
2665         # fmtlist, 49*nvar, char array
2666         for fmt in self.fmtlist:
2667             self._write(_pad_bytes(fmt, 49))
2668 
2669     def _write_value_label_names(self) -> None:
2670         # lbllist, 33*nvar, char array
2671         for i in range(self.nvar):
2672             # Use variable name when categorical
2673             if self._is_col_cat[i]:
2674                 name = self.varlist[i]
2675                 name = self._null_terminate_str(name)
2676                 name = _pad_bytes(name[:32], 33)
2677                 self._write(name)
2678             else:  # Default is empty label
2679                 self._write(_pad_bytes("", 33))
2680 
2681     def _write_variable_labels(self) -> None:
2682         # Missing labels are 80 blank characters plus null termination
2683         blank = _pad_bytes("", 81)
2684 
2685         if self._variable_labels is None:
2686             for i in range(self.nvar):
2687                 self._write(blank)
2688             return
2689 
2690         for col in self.data:
2691             if col in self._variable_labels:
2692                 label = self._variable_labels[col]
2693                 if len(label) > 80:
2694                     raise ValueError("Variable labels must be 80 characters or fewer")
2695                 is_latin1 = all(ord(c) < 256 for c in label)
2696                 if not is_latin1:
2697                     raise ValueError(
2698                         "Variable labels must contain only characters that "
2699                         "can be encoded in Latin-1"
2700                     )
2701                 self._write(_pad_bytes(label, 81))
2702             else:
2703                 self._write(blank)
2704 
2705     def _convert_strls(self, data: DataFrame) -> DataFrame:
2706         """No-op, future compatibility"""
2707         return data

2709     def _prepare_data(self) -> np.recarray:
2710         data = self.data
2711         typlist = self.typlist
2712         convert_dates = self._convert_dates
2713         # 1. Convert dates
2714         if self._convert_dates is not None:
2715             for i, col in enumerate(data):
2716                 if i in convert_dates:
2717                     data[col] = _datetime_to_stata_elapsed_vec(
2718                         data[col], self.fmtlist[i]
2719                     )
2720         # 2. Convert strls
2721         data = self._convert_strls(data)
2722 
2723         # 3. Convert bad string data to '' and pad to correct length
2724         dtypes = {}
2725         native_byteorder = self._byteorder == _set_endianness(sys.byteorder)
2726         for i, col in enumerate(data):
2727             typ = typlist[i]
2728             if typ <= self._max_string_length:
2729                 data[col] = data[col].fillna("").apply(_pad_bytes, args=(typ,))
2730                 stype = f"S{typ}"
2731                 dtypes[col] = stype
2732                 data[col] = data[col].astype(stype)
2733             else:
2734                 dtype = data[col].dtype
2735                 if not native_byteorder:
2736                     dtype = dtype.newbyteorder(self._byteorder)
2737                 dtypes[col] = dtype
2738 
2739         return data.to_records(index=False, column_dtypes=dtypes)
2740 
2741     def _write_data(self, records: np.recarray) -> None:
2742         self._write_bytes(records.tobytes())

2744     @staticmethod
2745     def _null_terminate_str(s: str) -> str:
2746         s += "\x00"
2747         return s

2749     def _null_terminate_bytes(self, s: str) -> bytes:
2750         return self._null_terminate_str(s).encode(self._encoding)

2753 def _dtype_to_stata_type_117(dtype: np.dtype, column: Series, force_strl: bool) -> int:
2754     """
2755     Converts dtype types to stata types. Returns the byte of the given ordinal.
2756     See TYPE_MAP and comments for an explanation. This is also explained in
2757     the dta spec.
2758     1 - 2045 are strings of this length
2759                 Pandas    Stata
2760     32768 - for object    strL
2761     65526 - for int8      byte
2762     65527 - for int16     int
2763     65528 - for int32     long
2764     65529 - for float32   float
2765     65530 - for double    double
2766 
2767     If there are dates to convert, then dtype will already have the correct
2768     type inserted.
2769     """
2770     # TODO: expand to handle datetime to integer conversion
2771     if force_strl:
2772         return 32768
2773     if dtype.type == np.object_:  # try to coerce it to the biggest string
2774         # not memory efficient, what else could we
2775         # do?
2776         itemsize = max_len_string_array(ensure_object(column._values))
2777         itemsize = max(itemsize, 1)
2778         if itemsize <= 2045:
2779             return itemsize
2780         return 32768
2781     elif dtype == np.float64:
2782         return 65526
2783     elif dtype == np.float32:
2784         return 65527
2785     elif dtype == np.int32:
2786         return 65528
2787     elif dtype == np.int16:
2788         return 65529
2789     elif dtype == np.int8:
2790         return 65530
2791     else:  # pragma : no cover
2792         raise NotImplementedError(f"Data type {dtype} not supported.")
2793 
2794 
2795 def _pad_bytes_new(name: Union[str, bytes], length: int) -> bytes:
2796     """
2797     Takes a bytes instance and pads it with null bytes until it's length chars.
2798     """
2799     if isinstance(name, str):
2800         name = bytes(name, "utf-8")
2801     return name + b"\x00" * (length - len(name))

2804 class StataStrLWriter:
2805     """
2806     Converter for Stata StrLs
2807 
2808     Stata StrLs map 8 byte values to strings which are stored using a
2809     dictionary-like format where strings are keyed to two values.
2810 
2811     Parameters
2812     ----------
2813     df : DataFrame
2814         DataFrame to convert
2815     columns : Sequence[str]
2816         List of columns names to convert to StrL
2817     version : int, optional
2818         dta version.  Currently supports 117, 118 and 119
2819     byteorder : str, optional
2820         Can be ">", "<", "little", or "big". default is `sys.byteorder`
2821 
2822     Notes
2823     -----
2824     Supports creation of the StrL block of a dta file for dta versions
2825     117, 118 and 119.  These differ in how the GSO is stored.  118 and
2826     119 store the GSO lookup value as a uint32 and a uint64, while 117
2827     uses two uint32s. 118 and 119 also encode all strings as unicode
2828     which is required by the format.  117 uses 'latin-1' a fixed width
2829     encoding that extends the 7-bit ascii table with an additional 128
2830     characters.
2831     """
2832 
2833     def __init__(
2834         self,
2835         df: DataFrame,
2836         columns: Sequence[str],
2837         version: int = 117,
2838         byteorder: Optional[str] = None,
2839     ):
2840         if version not in (117, 118, 119):
2841             raise ValueError("Only dta versions 117, 118 and 119 supported")
2842         self._dta_ver = version
2843 
2844         self.df = df
2845         self.columns = columns
2846         self._gso_table = {"": (0, 0)}
2847         if byteorder is None:
2848             byteorder = sys.byteorder
2849         self._byteorder = _set_endianness(byteorder)
2850 
2851         gso_v_type = "I"  # uint32
2852         gso_o_type = "Q"  # uint64
2853         self._encoding = "utf-8"
2854         if version == 117:
2855             o_size = 4
2856             gso_o_type = "I"  # 117 used uint32
2857             self._encoding = "latin-1"
2858         elif version == 118:
2859             o_size = 6
2860         else:  # version == 119
2861             o_size = 5
2862         self._o_offet = 2 ** (8 * (8 - o_size))
2863         self._gso_o_type = gso_o_type
2864         self._gso_v_type = gso_v_type
2865 
2866     def _convert_key(self, key: Tuple[int, int]) -> int:
2867         v, o = key
2868         return v + self._o_offet * o
2869 
2870     def generate_table(self) -> Tuple[Dict[str, Tuple[int, int]], DataFrame]:
2871         """
2872         Generates the GSO lookup table for the DataFrame
2873 
2874         Returns
2875         -------
2876         gso_table : dict
2877             Ordered dictionary using the string found as keys
2878             and their lookup position (v,o) as values
2879         gso_df : DataFrame
2880             DataFrame where strl columns have been converted to
2881             (v,o) values
2882 
2883         Notes
2884         -----
2885         Modifies the DataFrame in-place.
2886 
2887         The DataFrame returned encodes the (v,o) values as uint64s. The
2888         encoding depends on the dta version, and can be expressed as
2889 
2890         enc = v + o * 2 ** (o_size * 8)
2891 
2892         so that v is stored in the lower bits and o is in the upper
2893         bits. o_size is
2894 
2895           * 117: 4
2896           * 118: 6
2897           * 119: 5
2898         """
2899         gso_table = self._gso_table
2900         gso_df = self.df
2901         columns = list(gso_df.columns)
2902         selected = gso_df[self.columns]
2903         col_index = [(col, columns.index(col)) for col in self.columns]
2904         keys = np.empty(selected.shape, dtype=np.uint64)
2905         for o, (idx, row) in enumerate(selected.iterrows()):
2906             for j, (col, v) in enumerate(col_index):
2907                 val = row[col]
2908                 # Allow columns with mixed str and None (GH 23633)
2909                 val = "" if val is None else val
2910                 key = gso_table.get(val, None)
2911                 if key is None:
2912                     # Stata prefers human numbers
2913                     key = (v + 1, o + 1)
2914                     gso_table[val] = key
2915                 keys[o, j] = self._convert_key(key)
2916         for i, col in enumerate(self.columns):
2917             gso_df[col] = keys[:, i]
2918 
2919         return gso_table, gso_df
2920 
2921     def generate_blob(self, gso_table: Dict[str, Tuple[int, int]]) -> bytes:
2922         """
2923         Generates the binary blob of GSOs that is written to the dta file.
2924 
2925         Parameters
2926         ----------
2927         gso_table : dict
2928             Ordered dictionary (str, vo)
2929 
2930         Returns
2931         -------
2932         gso : bytes
2933             Binary content of dta file to be placed between strl tags
2934 
2935         Notes
2936         -----
2937         Output format depends on dta version.  117 uses two uint32s to
2938         express v and o while 118+ uses a uint32 for v and a uint64 for o.
2939         """
2940         # Format information
2941         # Length includes null term
2942         # 117
2943         # GSOvvvvooootllllxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx...x
2944         #  3  u4  u4 u1 u4  string + null term
2945         #
2946         # 118, 119
2947         # GSOvvvvooooooootllllxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx...x
2948         #  3  u4   u8   u1 u4    string + null term
2949 
2950         bio = BytesIO()
2951         gso = bytes("GSO", "ascii")
2952         gso_type = struct.pack(self._byteorder + "B", 130)
2953         null = struct.pack(self._byteorder + "B", 0)
2954         v_type = self._byteorder + self._gso_v_type
2955         o_type = self._byteorder + self._gso_o_type
2956         len_type = self._byteorder + "I"
2957         for strl, vo in gso_table.items():
2958             if vo == (0, 0):
2959                 continue
2960             v, o = vo
2961 
2962             # GSO
2963             bio.write(gso)
2964 
2965             # vvvv
2966             bio.write(struct.pack(v_type, v))
2967 
2968             # oooo / oooooooo
2969             bio.write(struct.pack(o_type, o))
2970 
2971             # t
2972             bio.write(gso_type)
2973 
2974             # llll
2975             utf8_string = bytes(strl, "utf-8")
2976             bio.write(struct.pack(len_type, len(utf8_string) + 1))
2977 
2978             # xxx...xxx
2979             bio.write(utf8_string)
2980             bio.write(null)
2981 
2982         bio.seek(0)
2983         return bio.read()
2984

2986 class StataWriter117(StataWriter):
2987     """
2988     A class for writing Stata binary dta files in Stata 13 format (117)
2989 
2990     .. versionadded:: 0.23.0
2991 
2992     Parameters
2993     ----------
2994     fname : path (string), buffer or path object
2995         string, path object (pathlib.Path or py._path.local.LocalPath) or
2996         object implementing a binary write() functions. If using a buffer
2997         then the buffer will not be automatically closed after the file
2998         is written.
2999     data : DataFrame
3000         Input to save
3001     convert_dates : dict
3002         Dictionary mapping columns containing datetime types to stata internal
3003         format to use when writing the dates. Options are 'tc', 'td', 'tm',
3004         'tw', 'th', 'tq', 'ty'. Column can be either an integer or a name.

3006         converted to 'tc'. Raises NotImplementedError if a datetime column has
3007         timezone information
3008     write_index : bool

3010     byteorder : str
3011         Can be ">", "<", "little", or "big". default is `sys.byteorder`
3012     time_stamp : datetime
3013         A datetime to use as file creation date.  Default is the current time
3014     data_label : str
3015         A label for the data set.  Must be 80 characters or smaller.
3016     variable_labels : dict
3017         Dictionary containing columns as keys and variable labels as values.
3018         Each label must be 80 characters or smaller.
3019     convert_strl : list
3020         List of columns names to convert to Stata StrL format.  Columns with
3021         more than 2045 characters are automatically written as StrL.
3022         Smaller columns can be converted by including the column name.  Using
3023         StrLs can reduce output file size when strings are longer than 8

3121     def _write_header(
3122         self,
3123         data_label: Optional[str] = None,
3124         time_stamp: Optional[datetime.datetime] = None,
3125     ) -> None:
3126         """Write the file header"""
3127         byteorder = self._byteorder
3128         self._write_bytes(bytes("<stata_dta>", "utf-8"))
3129         bio = BytesIO()
3130         # ds_format - 117
3131         bio.write(self._tag(bytes(str(self._dta_version), "utf-8"), "release"))
3132         # byteorder
3133         bio.write(self._tag(byteorder == ">" and "MSF" or "LSF", "byteorder"))
3134         # number of vars, 2 bytes in 117 and 118, 4 byte in 119
3135         nvar_type = "H" if self._dta_version <= 118 else "I"
3136         bio.write(self._tag(struct.pack(byteorder + nvar_type, self.nvar), "K"))
3137         # 117 uses 4 bytes, 118 uses 8
3138         nobs_size = "I" if self._dta_version == 117 else "Q"
3139         bio.write(self._tag(struct.pack(byteorder + nobs_size, self.nobs), "N"))
3140         # data label 81 bytes, char, null terminated
3141         label = data_label[:80] if data_label is not None else ""
3142         encoded_label = label.encode(self._encoding)
3143         label_size = "B" if self._dta_version == 117 else "H"
3144         label_len = struct.pack(byteorder + label_size, len(encoded_label))
3145         encoded_label = label_len + encoded_label
3146         bio.write(self._tag(encoded_label, "label"))
3147         # time stamp, 18 bytes, char, null terminated
3148         # format dd Mon yyyy hh:mm
3149         if time_stamp is None:
3150             time_stamp = datetime.datetime.now()
3151         elif not isinstance(time_stamp, datetime.datetime):
3152             raise ValueError("time_stamp should be datetime type")
3153         # Avoid locale-specific month conversion
3154         months = [
3155             "Jan",
3156             "Feb",
3157             "Mar",
3158             "Apr",
3159             "May",
3160             "Jun",
3161             "Jul",
3162             "Aug",
3163             "Sep",
3164             "Oct",
3165             "Nov",
3166             "Dec",
3167         ]
3168         month_lookup = {i + 1: month for i, month in enumerate(months)}
3169         ts = (
3170             time_stamp.strftime("%d ")
3171             + month_lookup[time_stamp.month]
3172             + time_stamp.strftime(" %Y %H:%M")
3173         )
3174         # '\x11' added due to inspection of Stata file
3175         stata_ts = b"\x11" + bytes(ts, "utf-8")
3176         bio.write(self._tag(stata_ts, "timestamp"))
3177         bio.seek(0)
3178         self._write_bytes(self._tag(bio.read(), "header"))

3181         """
3182         Called twice during file write. The first populates the values in
3183         the map with 0s.  The second call writes the final map locations when
3184         all blocks have been written.
3185         """
3186         assert self._file is not None
3187         if not self._map:
3188             self._map = dict(
3189                 (
3190                     ("stata_data", 0),

3192                     ("variable_types", 0),
3193                     ("varnames", 0),
3194                     ("sortlist", 0),
3195                     ("formats", 0),
3196                     ("value_label_names", 0),

3199                     ("data", 0),
3200                     ("strls", 0),
3201                     ("value_labels", 0),
3202                     ("stata_data_close", 0),

3377 class StataWriterUTF8(StataWriter117):

3379     Stata binary dta file writing in Stata 15 (118) and 16 (119) formats

3381     DTA 118 and 119 format files support unicode string data (both fixed
3382     and strL) format. Unicode is also supported in value labels, variable
3383     labels and the dataset label. Format 119 is automatically used if the
3384     file contains more than 32,767 variables.
3385 
3386     .. versionadded:: 1.0.0
3387 
3388     Parameters
3389     ----------
3390     fname : path (string), buffer or path object

3402         converted to 'tc'. Raises NotImplementedError if a datetime column has
3403         timezone information

3518     def _validate_variable_name(self, name: str) -> str:
3519         """
3520         Validate variable names for Stata export.
3521 
3522         Parameters
3523         ----------
3524         name : str
3525             Variable name
3526 
3527         Returns
3528         -------
3529         str
3530             The validated name with invalid characters replaced with
3531             underscores.
3532 
3533         Notes
3534         -----
3535         Stata 118+ support most unicode characters. The only limitation is in
3536         the ascii range where the characters supported are a-z, A-Z, 0-9 and _.
3537         """
3538         # High code points appear to be acceptable
3539         for c in name:
3540             if (
3541                 ord(c) < 128
3542                 and (c < "A" or c > "Z")
3543                 and (c < "a" or c > "z")
3544                 and (c < "0" or c > "9")
3545                 and c != "_"
3546             ) or 128 <= ord(c) < 256:
3547                 name = name.replace(c, "_")
3548
